'''Cancer Bats''' are a [[hardcore punk]] band from Toronto, Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cancerbats.com |title=Cancer Bats Official Fan Hub - Powered by SocialMediaHubs.com |publisher=Cancerbats.com |date= |accessdate=2011-12-07}}</ref> They have released four [[studio album]]s and six [[extended plays]]. The band is composed of vocalist Liam Cormier, guitarist Scott Middleton, [[drummer]] Mike Peters and bassist [[Jaye R. Schwarzer]]. Cancer Bats take a wide variety of influences from [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] sub-genres and fuse them into [[hardcore punk]] and [[punk rock]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theagencygroup.com/artist.aspx?ArtistID=3163 |title=Cancer Bats|publisher=[[The Agency Group]] |author= |date= |accessdate=February 11, 2012}}</ref> and include elements of [[sludge metal]],<ref name="BBC B,M,S,B review">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/b5rj |title=Cancer Bats Review on BBC|author=Ben Patashnik|work=[[BBC Music]]|accessdate=2010-06-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/cancer-bats-mn0000718386|title=Cancer Bats - biography|website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 29, 2012}}</ref> and [[southern rock]].<ref name="Pop B,M,S,B review">{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/124378-cancer-bats-bears-mayors-scraps-bones/|title=Cancer Bats: Bears, Mayors, Scraps & Bones|last=Colgan|first=Chris|date=May 5, 2010|publisher=[[PopMatters]]|accessdate=June 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maplemusic.com/artists/can/bio.asp|title=Cancer Bats - bio|publisher=[[Maplemusic]]|accessdate=October 29, 2012}}</ref> The band has also been compared to metalcore bands of the 1990s like [[Converge (band)|Converge]] and [[Hatebreed]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2010/03/24/cancer-bats-vocalist-liam-cormier-the-metalsucks-interview/|title=CANCER BATS<U+2019> VOCALIST LIAM CORMIER: THE METALSUCKS INTERVIEW|author= Vince Neilstein|date=March 24, 2010|publisher=[[MetalSucks]]|accessdate=February 11, 2012}}</ref>

==History==
===Early years and ''Birthing the Giant'' (2004<U+2013>2006)<span id="Early years and Birthing the Giant"></span>===
Cancer Bats originated in May 2004 with singer [[Liam Cormier]] and guitarist [[Scott Middleton]], former member of Toronto [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[At the Mercy of Inspiration]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/features/178.htm |title=Alternative Press interview |publisher=Altpress.com |date= |accessdate=2011-03-10}}</ref> The two wanted to form a project that combined their favorite parts of bands like [[Refused]], [[Black Flag (band)|Black Flag]], [[Led Zeppelin]] and [[Down (band)|Down]], among others. The lineup was rounded out with the addition of [[Andrew McCracken]] on bass and [[Joel Bath]] on drums. The four-piece wasted no time writing and recording songs for a self-released demo that saw light in January 2005.

The story is that the band considered the names ''Cancer Bats'' and ''Pneumonia Hawk'' after deciding that a combination of illness and animal name would give the best band name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/mikedavies/tracklistingarchive.shtml?20080527 |title=BBC Radio 1 punk show 27th of May 2008 |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2011-03-10}}</ref> Soon after, Mike Peters replaced Bath on the drums and the band began playing throughout Southern [[Ontario]], playing live shows with bands like [[Billy Talent]], [[Every Time I Die]], [[NORA (band)|Nora]], [[Alexisonfire]], [[Haste the Day]], [[It Dies Today]], [[Bane (band)|Bane]], [[Comeback Kid]], [[Buried Inside]], [[Attack in Black]], [[Misery Signals]], [[This Is Hell (band)|This Is Hell]], [[Rise Against]], [[The Bronx (band)|The Bronx]] and [[Gallows (band)|Gallows]].

On June 2, 2006, the band took part in a short interview and then played a free CD release show at The Edge 102.1 ([[CFNY-FM]]) and then on June 6 ''[[Birthing the Giant]]'' was released into major record stores. The album includes guest vocals by [[George Pettit]] of [[Alexisonfire]]. On June 7, 2006 they hosted [[All Things Rock]], a show on MTV Canada, and had their own video played at the end of the show.<ref>[http://www.mtv.ca/?id=1533623 MTV overdrive page] showing performance.</ref>

===Lineup changes and ''Hail Destroyer'' (2007<U+2013>2008)<span id="Lineup changes/Hail Destroyer"></span>===
Bass player [[Andrew McCracken]] left to concentrate on his design company [http://www.doublenaut.com Doublenaut]. His spot was filled in by [[Jason Bailey]] (former member of bands [[Figure Four]] and [[Shattered Realm]]) for most of 2007 after which he was replaced by [[Jaye R. Schwarzer]], who is formerly of '''Left Behind''', '''Hope to Die''', '''Minesweeper''', '''Kover''', and currently a '''Reefer Cathedral''' member alongside Cancer Bats guitarist Scott Middleton.

[[File:LiamCormier.JPG|thumb|right|Cormier performing at a Cancer Bats show in Barcelona in June 2008.]]
The band released their second studio album called ''[[Hail Destroyer]]'' on April 22, 2008. The album features guest vocals by [[Wade MacNeil]] of [[Alexisonfire]] and [[Black Lungs]], [[Tim McIlrath]] of [[Rise Against]] and [[Ben Kowalewicz]] of [[Billy Talent]]. The release was held at the Mod Club in downtown Toronto with [[Liam Cormier]] not only singing for Cancer Bats, but also performing drums for [[Black Lungs]]. On May 17, 2008, Cancer Bats were put on the cover of ''[[Kerrang!]]'', a publication which gave their album ''Hail Destroyer'' a KKKKK review (highest possible) as well as a 5k Live review on their headlining UK tour. Cancer Bats were also nominated for 2008 Album of the Year for the 2008 Kerrang! awards.

Cancer Bats have performed at the [[Download Festival]] in 2007, [[Groezrock]] 2007 and at both [[Reading and Leeds Festivals]] in 2007 and 2008. In the summer of 2008, the band did an extensive summer and autumn tour with [[Bullet for My Valentine]], [[Black Tide]] and [[Bleeding Through]], as part of the [[No Fear]] music tour across North America. Also in 2008, they were a support act for Welsh band [[Funeral for a Friend]] during their tour of Britain and northern Europe.

===Touring and ''Bears, Mayors, Scraps & Bones'' (2009<U+2013>2011)<span id="Bears, Mayors, Scraps & Bones"></span>===
In March 2009, they went on tour at the annual [[Taste of Chaos]] festival along with [[Thursday (band)|Thursday]], [[Four Year Strong]], [[Pierce the Veil]] and [[Bring Me the Horizon]], keeping a daily blog on their website. At about this time Cancer Bats were also featured in Bring Me the Horizon's video for "[[Chelsea Smile]]", in which they appear in the "Kitchen Scene" of the video playing cards. Also in March, Liam Cormier lent his vocals to sing on fellow Canadian band [[Silverstein (band)|Silverstein]]'s fourth studio album ''[[A Shipwreck in the Sand]]'' on the track "[[Vices (Silverstein song)|Vices]]".<ref name="AlterThePress">{{cite web|last=Reid |first=Sean |url=http://www.alterthepress.com/2009/03/interview-cancer-bats-3032009.html |title=Interview: Cancer Bats - 3/03/2009 |publisher=Alter the Press! |date=March 3, 2009 |accessdate=2011-03-10}}</ref>

Cancer Bats returned to the UK in 2009, after Swedish melodic metal band [[In Flames]] cancelled their April 2009 concerts, on which Cancer Bats were slated to be main support.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.kerrang.com/2009/02/in_flames_cancel_upcoming_uk_t.html |title=In Flames cancel upcoming UK/Ireland tour |publisher=Kerrang! |date=February 18, 2009 |accessdate=2011-12-07}}</ref> The band is also featured on [[Gallows (band)|Gallows]]' latest album ''[[Grey Britain]]'' on May 2.<ref name="AlterThePress"/> In August 1, Cancer Bats played a slot at the premier showing of the Sonisphere festival and at the inaugural [[Hevy Music Festival]]. Also in 2009, Cancer Bats appeared in an episode of the documentary series ''[[City Sonic]]'', reflecting on their time at the Adrift Clubhouse. In October and November, the band supported [[Billy Talent]] on their UK and European tour. During the tour they performed several new songs from their third album, including "Darkness"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QDPUIgSxyRY |title=New song: Darkness |publisher=Youtube.com |date=November 21, 2009 |accessdate=2011-03-10}}</ref> and "Scared to Death".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zHbJOJ8iBSo |title=New song: Scared to Death |publisher=Youtube.com |date= |accessdate=2011-03-10}}</ref>

In January and February 2010, the band toured the US supporting [[Anti-Flag]]. Following that tour they joined fellow Canadians [[Billy Talent]], [[Alexisonfire]] and the American band [[Against Me!]] on a tour across Canada throughout March.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=blog.view&friendId=6435604&blogId=525492679 |title=CANADIAN TOUR w/ Billy Talent, Alexisonfire, & Against Me! van Cancer Bats op Myspace |publisher=Blogs.myspace.com |date=January 11, 2010 |accessdate=2011-12-07}}</ref> Cancer Bats released their third album ''[[Bears, Mayors, Scraps & Bones]]'' on April 12 in the UK.<ref name="TrackByTrack"/> On March, the band did a track by track talk with [[Rock Sound]].<ref name="TrackByTrack">{{cite web|url=http://www.rocksound.tv/news/article/track-by-track-cancer-bats |title=Track By Track: Cancer Bats &#124; News &#124; Rock Sound |publisher=Rocksound.tv |date= |accessdate=2011-03-10}}</ref> A music video was shot for their cover of the [[Beastie Boys]] song "[[Sabotage (song)|Sabotage]]", a track recorded for the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theprp.com/tag/iii-bears-mayors-scraps-bones/ |title=III: Bears Mayors Scraps & Bones |publisher=Theprp.com |date= |accessdate=2011-03-10}}</ref> In September of the same year they opened for [[Bring Me the Horizon]] on their UK tour along with [[Tek One]].

In late 2011, Cancer Bats toured Canada as a [[Black Sabbath]] [[tribute band]] under the moniker "Bat Sabbath".<ref>{{cite web| last = Semley| first = John| title = Interview: Cancer Bats/Bat Sabbath| work = [[The A.V. Club]]| publisher = [[The Onion]]| date = December 2, 2011| url = http://www.avclub.com/toronto/articles/cancer-batsbat-sabbath%2c65771/| accessdate = December 2, 2011}}</ref> The concept stated at [[Sonisphere Festival#UK|Sonisphere Festival]] on July 10, 2011 when the band was asked to do an after-party show, on top of their initial set in the afternoon, in the tent stage after [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]] played the main stage. The dates they performed at for the Sonisphere were the last dates they did before they stopped to work on a follow up to their third studio album.<ref name= "NME 1"/> After the performances at the various Sonisphere dates they did a 12 date Canadian tour in December 2011 centred around the Black Sabbath tribute.<ref name="Blare 1">{{cite web|url=http://blaremagazine.com/2011/12/12/interview-cancer-bats/|title=INTERVIEW: Cancer Bats <U+00AB>|author= Vince Neilstein|date=March 24, 2010|publisher=[[Blare Magazine]]|accessdate=February 11, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| last = Hughes| first = Josiah| title = Cancer Bats to Bring Their Bat Sabbath on Canadian Tour| work = [[Exclaim!]]| date = November 1, 2011| url = http://exclaim.ca/News/cancer_bats_to_bring_their_bat_sabbath_on_canadian_tour| accessdate = December 2, 2011}}</ref>

===''Dead Set on Living'' (2012<U+2013>present)<span id="Dead Set on Living (2012 <U+2013> present)"></span>===
The band announced that the fourth album is titled ''[[Dead Set on Living]]'',<ref name= "NME 2">{{cite web|url= http://www.nme.com/news/cancer-bats/61235|title= Cancer Bats to play six London shows in one day|author= |publisher= [[New Musical Express]]|date= January 4, 2012|accessdate= January 4, 2012}}</ref> which was released in April 16, 2012. Cancer Bats had stated that they desired to create a more "upbeat" follow up to their previous album ''Bears, Mayors, Scraps & Bones''.<ref name= "NME 1">{{cite web|url= http://www.nme.com/news/cancer-bats/57910|title= Cancer Bats at Sonisphere: 'We're ready to party on our new album'|author= |publisher= [[New Musical Express]]|date= July 10, 2011|accessdate= January 4, 2012}}</ref>

The band's influence steered away from the "traditional hardcore record" and took a wide variety of influences from rock bands including [[Fleet Foxes]]. Liam Cormier when asked about his influences stated: "In a lot of ways we get really inspired by non-metal bands. For me, I find I really like looking at other things because I just don't want to make a traditional hardcore record lyrically. So for me, I listen to a lot of indie rock and I've been getting super psyched on a lot of that, like the new 'Helplessness Blues' by Fleet Foxes".<ref name= "NME 3">{{cite web|url= http://www.nme.com/news/cancer-bats/60717|title= Cancer Bats: 'Fleet Foxes have inspired our new album'|author= |publisher= [[New Musical Express]]|date= December 1, 2011|accessdate= January 4, 2012}}</ref>

On January 24, Distort Entertainment released the video for the single "Old Blood" online.<ref name="Old Blood Release">{{cite web|url=http://www.teamdistort.com/news/216/|title=DISTORT: NEWS Cancer Bats release video for lead single "Old Blood"|publisher=[[Distort Entertainment]]|date=January 24, 2012|accessdate=January 25, 2012}}</ref> On March 7, 2012 Cancer Bats released a second music video in promotion of the album for the song "Road Sick".<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/news/cancer-bats-release-fucking-awesome-road-sick-video/ | title = Cancer Bats Release <U+2018>Road Sick<U+2019> Video | author = Merlin | work = | publisher = [[Metal Hammer]] | date = March 8, 2012  | accessdate = March 25, 2012 | quote = }}</ref> Cancer Bats' announced that they would play several release shows on April 21, 2012. They have aimed to play in six different venues across London, United Kingdom, in the shape of a pentagram in promotion of their fourth album.<ref name= "NME 2"/>

==Recordings==
The band have released four albums. ''[[Birthing the Giant]]'' was their first full-length album. It was released on June 6, 2006 by [[Distort Entertainment]] in Canada and September 5, 2006 by [[Abacus Recordings]] in the US. Videos were shot for "100 Grand Canyon", "French Immersion" and "Pneumonia Hawk". ''[[Hail Destroyer]]'' was the band's second full-length album.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jiwani |first=Shehzaad |url=http://www.chartattack.com/news/53174/cancer-bats-dish-out-details-on-hail-destroyer-album |title=Chart attack article |publisher=Chart attack article |date=February 4, 2008 |accessdate=2011-03-10}}</ref> It was released on April 22, 2008 by [[Distort Entertainment]] in Canada and on June 24, 2008 by [[Metal Blade Records]] in the US.<ref>{{cite web|author=Be the first to comment |url=http://www.exclaim.ca/articles/generalarticlesynopsfullart.aspx?csid1=118&csid2=988&fid1=29767 |title=Interview on Exclaim.ca (video) |publisher=Exclaim.ca |date=February 13, 2008 |accessdate=2011-03-10}}</ref> ''[[Bears, Mayors, Scraps & Bones]]'' was released on April 13, 2010 through [[Distort Entertainment]] in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|author=dblnaut |url=http://www.teamdistort.com/discography/de20/ |title=Distort Releases |publisher=Teamdistort.com |date=April 13, 2010 |accessdate=2011-03-10}}</ref> The name of the album derives from each of the band members personal nickname (Mike - Bear; Scott - Mayor; Liam - Scraps; Jaye - Bones).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eyeweekly.com/music/music/article/86217 |title=Eye Weekly interview |publisher=Eyeweekly.com |date=March 24, 2010 |accessdate=2011-03-10}}</ref>

They have also released five singles and EPs. ''[[Cancer Bats (EP)|Cancer Bats]]'' was the first EP by the band. It was produced and engineered by guitarist Scott Middleton. This EP was sold at all the live shows leading up until the release of Cancer Bats' first album ''Birthing the Giant'' and later repressed as a 7" record by Tragicomedy Records. ''[[This Is Hell / Cancer Bats]]'' was a limited release 7" vinyl EP shared with the [[This Is Hell (band)|This Is Hell]] band. Each band contributes one new song, and one cover song of the other band.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.futuretenserecords.com/ |title=Futuretense Records |publisher=futuretenserecords.com |date= |accessdate=2011-12-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trustkill.com/artist/This+Is+Hell |title=Bullet Tooth |publisher=Trustkill.com |date= |accessdate=2011-12-07}}</ref> ''[[Rolo Tomassi / Cancer Bats Split|Cancer Bats / Rolo Tomassi]]'' was a split release with the band [[Rolo Tomassi]] in 2009. The songs were recorded and released at the beginning of 2009 on to a limited amount of black 7" [[gramophone record|vinyl]] through [[Hassle Records]]. The vinyl is strictly limited to 300 copies and was only available through each artist's shows, and [[Rolo Tomassi]]'s 'Subs Club' 7" (2009).<ref name="alterthepress1">{{cite web|last=Reid |first=Sean |url=http://www.alterthepress.com/2009/02/limited-edition-cancer-batsrolo-tomassi.html |title=Limited Edition Cancer Bats/Rolo Tomassi Split 7" Announced |publisher=Alterthepress.com |date= |accessdate=2011-03-10}}</ref> Cancer Bats also released the ''Tour EP'' (2009).<ref name="chartattack1">{{cite web|last=Marcus |first=Bianca |url=http://www.chartattack.com/news/70286/cancer-bats-releasing-tour-ep |title=Cancer Bats Releasing Tour EP |publisher=Chartattack.com |date=May 27, 2009 |accessdate=2011-03-10}}</ref> In March 2, 2010, Cancer Bats released the ''Sabotage EP''.<ref name="teamdistort1">{{cite web|author=dblnaut |url=http://www.teamdistort.com/discography/dd22/ |title=Distort Releases: Sabotage EP |publisher=Teamdistort.com |date=March 2, 2010 |accessdate=2011-03-10}}</ref> Its name is derived from their cover of the [[Beastie Boys]]' song "[[Sabotage (song)|Sabotage]]". The band has also shot a music video for the song that premi<U+00E8>red on February 16 through the band's MySpace page.

==Band members==
